b'' b'thanks to bruce barnett, who recommended xvttool, and bernward averwald and' b'liam quin, who recommended modifying .xdefaults to get the desired behavior' b'for a *class* of xterms.' b'' b'in xvttool, simply create a key file that looks like:' b'"a"\t"a"' b'"b"\t"b"' b'"c"\t"c"' b'...' b'and specify said key file on the command line. this will translate' b'any input into any other (in my case, lo-case to up-case). works great, and' b'you get a customizable button-pad on the right or left side.' b'' b'to use an xterm solution, add to your .xdefaults:' b'capxterm*vt100.translations: #override b'<keya: string("a")\\n\\' b'...' b'' b'or:' b'capxterm.vt100.translations: #override \\n\\' b'<keya: insert-string(a) \\n\\' b'<keyb: insert-string(b) \\n\\' b'...' b'' b'and invoke as: xterm -name capxterm' b'' b'thanks loads!' b'--' b'kevin weinrich computer sciences corp.' 